{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"eb2259f0-7ac8-41f0-b699-499563a4d02c","content":"Here are the issues I found in the `template.json` file:\n\n1. **Missing `identity` field** (required) — Every .NET template must have a unique `identity` string (e.g., `\"identity\": \"Test.Template\"`).\n\n2. **Invalid `datatype`** — `\"invalid-type\"` on line 9 is not a recognized datatype. Valid values are: `bool`, `choice`, `float`, `int`, `hex`, `text`, `string`.\n\n3. **Risky `shortName`** — `\"build\"` conflicts with the built-in `dotnet build` command, which could shadow it. Consider a more unique name.\n\nThe most critical issues are **#1** (the template won't install without `identity`) and **#2** (the invalid datatype will cause parameter errors).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e8dd3aae-583b-42c2-ba7d-3aaf0f47377d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Let me analyze this template.json file. This is a .NET template configuration file used by `dotnet new`. Let me check for issues:\n\n1. **Missing `identity` field** — The `identity` field is required (or at least strongly recommended) for .NET templates. It uniquely identifies the template.\n2. **Missing `sourceName`** — Not strictly required, but commonly used.\n3. **Invalid `datatype`** — The `datatype` value `\"invalid-type\"` is not a valid datatype. Valid datatypes for .NET template parameters include: `bool`, `choice`, `float`, `int`, `hex`, `text`, `string`.\n\n\n4. **`shortName` conflicts with built-in command** — Using `\"build\"` as the shortName will clash with the existing `dotnet build` command, which could cause confusion or errors when users try to invoke the template.\n\nI should also look at what other files are in the working directory to get a fuller picture of the template structure.","outputTokens":535,"requestId":"2813:4D842:127743:185E51:69FFD7C9"},"id":"fb5bf3ae-a5c7-41d8-94b9-5048054999e0","timestamp":"2026-05-10T00:56:52.321Z","parentId":"07cb5f97-a0ff-4953-8071-66f0748efb3c"}
